   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0763.xml"/>the Rev. Samuel
            Furly</persName></head>
         <opener><placeName>Bristol</placeName><lb/><date when="1758-09-02">September 2, 1758</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>Dear Sammy,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p>I know no way to cure men of curiosity but to fill them with the love of God. If a great
            majority of those who attended the Thursday sermon were Methodists, I know not but it
            was right to put Mr.
            <persName>Charles</persName><!-- I could not identify this Mr. Charles through bios or ID -->
            in your place. Otherwise it would be wrong, for &apos;<index indexName="biblical">
               <term cRef="1Kings19:17">him that escapes the sword of Jehu shall Elisha slay</term>
            </index>&apos;.<note place="foot" n="1"><index indexName="biblical">
                  <term cRef="1Kings19:17">1 Kgs. 19:17</term>
               </index>.</note> Every preacher whom God has sent will have a message to some souls
            who have not been reached by any other. And the more persons attend his preaching the
            better, the more room there is for God to work.</p>
         <p>Mr.
            <persName>Jones</persName>&apos;s<!-- I believe this to be an author, thus did not find an ID that concretely matches this name. There are also a ton of Mr. Jones -->
            book I have found and will send by <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1462.xml"/>Jemmy
               Morgan</persName><!-- I confidently believe this is the itinerant James Morgan whom JW has referred to in the same way in the Matthew Errington letter of 1757-01-8  -->.
            Mr.
            <persName>Holloway</persName>&apos;s<!-- I suspect this to also be an author who does not have a corresponding XML ID. The only other Holloway also did not fit this time of the letter -->
            probably I shall find by and by.</p>
         <p>I wish you would carefully read over the <hi rend="italic">Directions for Married
               Persons</hi>.<note place="foot" n="2"><persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                  />JW</persName> published in <date when="1753">1753</date> an abridged edition of
                  <persName>William Whateley</persName>&apos;s <hi rend="italic"> Directions for
                  Married Persons: Describing the Duties Common to Both, and Peculiar to Each of
                  Them</hi> (orig., <date when="1619">1619</date>); see <hi rend="italic">Bibliography</hi>, No.
               165.i.</note> It is an excellent tract. You need to have your heart full of grace, or
            you will have your hands full of work. Universal watchfulness is absolutely necessary in
            order to our victory over any evil. Whatever you do, do with your might.</p>
         <closer>I am,<lb/>
            <signed>Your affectionate brother,<lb/><persName>J. Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
      </body>
   </text>
